  "prompt": "What are the legal definitions of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined as the process of making illegally obtained money (from criminal activities) appear legal by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems. Specific legal definitions vary by jurisdiction, but typically involve three key stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source of funds through complex transactions\n3. Integration: Reintroducing the \"cleaned\" money into the legitimate economy\n\nSpecific legal definitions often include:\n- Knowingly concealing or disguising the origin of criminal proceeds\n- Transferring or converting property derived from criminal activity\n- Attempting to structure financial transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n- Engaging in transactions designed to hide the source of criminal funds\n\nMost countries have anti-money laundering (AML) laws that criminalize these activities, with penalties including fines and imprisonment.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any specific aspect of money laundering definitions?",
